TITLE.0: Dynamics Explorer Spin-Scan Auroral Imager ultraviolet camera images

TEXT.2: The spin-scan auroral imagers (SAI) comprise three photometers which

TEXT.3: provide images of Earth at various wavelengths via interference filters

TEXT.4: mounted on a wheel and selected by ground command.  Two of the photometers

TEXT.5: provide visible wavelength images, and the third provides images at

TEXT.7: The three photometers are mounted on the spacecraft such that their

TEXT.8: fields of view are separated by about 120 degrees in a plane oriented

TEXT.9: perpendicular to the spin axis.  Each photometer in operation collects

TEXT.10: one scan line during each spacecraft rotation, with an internal mirror

TEXT.11: stepping once per rotation to start a new scan line.

TEXT.12: An auroral image is a nadir-centered two-dimensional pixel array

TEXT.13: provided by the spacecraft rotation and the photometer's stepping mirror

TEXT.14: which advances the field of view 0.25 degrees once per rotation in a

TEXT.15: direction perpendicular to the plane of rotation.  A change in mirror-

TEXT.16: stepping direction signals the start of a new image.  One, two, or

TEXT.17: three photometers may be in operation at one time.  The images from all

TEXT.18: operating photometers are telemetered simultaneously with image repetition

TEXT.19: rates that typically vary from about 3 to 12 minutes.

TEXT.20: One of the three imaging photometers is equipped with filters and a

TEXT.21: photocathode for observations at vacuum-ultraviolet wavelengths, in

TEXT.22: particular emissions of the Lyman-Birge-Hopfield band of molecular

TEXT.23: nitrogen at about 140 to 170 nm.  Imaging at these wavelengths allows

TEXT.24: coverage of the auroral oval in both the dark and sunlit ionospheres.

TEXT.25: The filter array for the vacuum-ultraviolet imaging photometer also

TEXT.26: includes filters for atomic hydrogen Lyman alpha at 121.6 nm and oxygen

TEXT.28: The full width of the fields of view of the photometers

TEXT.29: corresponding to a single pixel is 0.29 degrees.  An image frame

TEXT.30: consists of all scan lines obtained by mirror steps in one direction

TEXT.31: which deflect the field of view by 0.25 degrees per rotation.  The

TEXT.32: angular separation of two consecutive pixels in the direction of

TEXT.33: spacecraft rotation is about 0.23 degrees.  A full frame has 120

TEXT.34: scan lines or 30 degrees of width.  For routine processing the

TEXT.35: angular width along a scan line is 150 pixels, or about 34.5 degrees

TEXT.36: of length.  The frame width is occasionally adjusted to less than

Approximate intensity in kR is Intens_Table(Image_Counts(i,j)+1).The appearance of the actual count value 255 is rare.
